	<div class="intro-section">
		<p class="lead">Fences between neighboring properties can be a source of harmony or conflict. California's "Good Neighbor Fence Act" provides clear guidelines for sharing fence costs and responsibilities, but many homeowners remain unaware of their rights and obligations. This comprehensive guide explains California fence laws and how they apply to Stockton residents, helping you navigate fence decisions with confidence.</p>
	</div>

	<h2>Understanding California's Good Neighbor Fence Act</h2>
	<p>California Civil Code Sections 841-841.4 establish the legal framework for boundary fences between adjoining properties. Here's what every Stockton homeowner needs to know:</p>

	<h3>The Basic Principle: Equal Benefit, Equal Responsibility</h3>
	<p>Under California law, adjoining landowners share equal responsibility for maintaining reasonable boundary fences. When both properties benefit from a fence, both property owners should contribute equally to its construction and upkeep.</p>

	<h3>Key Provisions of the Law</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Presumption of Equal Benefit:</strong> Unless proven otherwise, the law presumes both properties benefit equally from a boundary fence</li>
		<li><strong>Cost Sharing:</strong> Each property owner is responsible for one-half of reasonable construction and maintenance costs</li>
		<li><strong>Notice Requirements:</strong> Specific written notice procedures must be followed before demanding contribution</li>
		<li><strong>Dispute Resolution:</strong> The law provides mechanisms for resolving disagreements</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>When the Law Applies</h2>

	<h3>Situations Covered</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>New fence construction on a shared property line</li>
		<li>Replacement of existing deteriorated boundary fences</li>
		<li>Major repairs to shared boundary fences</li>
		<li>Upgrades to existing fences when both parties benefit</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Exceptions to Cost Sharing</h3>
	<p>You may not be able to require your neighbor to pay if:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>The neighbor doesn't benefit from the fence (e.g., they have no need for containment)</li>
		<li>You're building a "spite fence" (intentionally to annoy)</li>
		<li>The fence exceeds what's reasonably necessary</li>
		<li>Proper notice procedures weren't followed</li>
		<li>The neighbor is a government entity (special rules apply)</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>The 30-Day Notice Requirement</h2>
	<p>Before you can legally require neighbor contribution, you must provide proper written notice:</p>

	<h3>What the Notice Must Include</h3>
	<ol>
		<li>Description of the problem with existing fence (or need for new fence)</li>
		<li>Proposed solution (repair, replacement, new construction)</li>
		<li>Estimated costs with supporting documentation</li>
		<li>Proposed timeline for the work</li>
		<li>Specific demand that neighbor contribute their share</li>
	</ol>

	<h3>Delivery Requirements</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Deliver notice at least 30 days before starting work</li>
		<li>Send via certified mail, return receipt requested</li>
		<li>Keep copies of all correspondence</li>
		<li>Consider also delivering in person with dated photos of exchange</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>What Happens After Notice</h3>
	<p>After receiving your notice, your neighbor may:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Agree:</strong> Work together on specifications and cost sharing</li>
		<li><strong>Propose alternatives:</strong> Suggest different materials, contractors, or approaches</li>
		<li><strong>Disagree:</strong> Challenge the need, cost, or their responsibility</li>
		<li><strong>Ignore:</strong> Fail to respond (you may proceed but collection may require legal action)</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Determining "Reasonable" Fence Costs</h2>
	<p>California law requires fences to be "reasonable"—but what does that mean?</p>

	<h3>Factors Courts Consider</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Typical fence costs in the neighborhood</li>
		<li>Local customs and standards</li>
		<li>HOA requirements that may mandate specific materials</li>
		<li>Both parties' legitimate needs (privacy, pets, pool safety)</li>
		<li>The condition of any existing fence</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>What's Typically Considered Reasonable</h3>
	<table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 20px 0;">
		<thead>
			<tr style="background-color: #f4f4f4;">
				<th style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd; text-align: left;">Situation</th>
				<th style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd; text-align: left;">Reasonable</th>
				<th style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd; text-align: left;">May Be Excessive</th>
			</tr>
		</thead>
		<tbody>
			<tr>
