				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Full replacement if repairable</td>
			</tr>
		</tbody>
	</table>

	<h3>Premium Upgrades</h3>
	<p>If you want something beyond what's "reasonable," you can still build it—you just can't require your neighbor to pay for the premium portion. For example:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>A standard 6' cedar fence might cost $30/linear foot</li>
		<li>You want a premium composite fence at $50/linear foot</li>
		<li>Your neighbor's share is half of the reasonable amount: $15/linear foot</li>
		<li>You pay the difference: $35/linear foot</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Property Line Issues</h2>

	<h3>Locating the Exact Boundary</h3>
	<p>Before building any fence, confirm the property line location:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Survey Markers:</strong> Look for iron stakes, pipes, or concrete monuments</li>
		<li><strong>Property Deed:</strong> Review your title documents for legal descriptions</li>
		<li><strong>County Records:</strong> San Joaquin County maintains property maps</li>
		<li><strong>Professional Survey:</strong> When in doubt, hire a licensed surveyor ($400-800)</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Where to Place the Fence</h3>
	<p>Three options exist for fence placement:</p>

	<p><strong>On the Property Line (Shared Fence):</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Both neighbors share ownership and responsibility</li>
		<li>Requires agreement from both parties for changes</li>
		<li>Cost sharing law applies</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Inside Your Property Line:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>You own the fence entirely</li>
		<li>No neighbor permission needed</li>
		<li>You lose a few inches of usable yard</li>
		<li>Neighbor cannot be required to contribute</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Inside Neighbor's Property Line:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>They own the fence—avoid this situation</li>
		<li>Could create adverse possession issues over time</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Stockton-Specific Regulations</h2>

	<h3>Stockton Municipal Code Fence Requirements</h3>
	<p>Beyond state law, Stockton has local regulations:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Height Limits:</strong> Generally 6 feet in backyards, 3-4 feet in front yards</li>
		<li><strong>Setbacks:</strong> Specific requirements near streets and corners for visibility</li>
		<li><strong>Materials:</strong> Some materials may be restricted in certain zones</li>
		<li><strong>Permits:</strong> Required for fences over 6 feet and in some locations</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>HOA Considerations</h3>
	<p>Many Stockton neighborhoods have HOAs with additional requirements:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Pre-approved materials, colors, and styles</li>
		<li>Required architectural review before installation</li>
		<li>Maintenance standards that must be met</li>
		<li>Uniform appearance requirements throughout neighborhood</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Important:</strong> HOA rules may supersede your preferences but don't eliminate Good Neighbor Fence Act obligations. Both neighbors must still share costs for HOA-compliant fencing.</p>

	<h2>Handling Neighbor Disputes</h2>

	<h3>Prevention is Best</h3>
	<p>Avoid disputes by:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Communicating early and openly about fence plans</li>
		<li>Sharing estimates from multiple contractors</li>
		<li>Considering your neighbor's aesthetic preferences</li>
		<li>Putting all agreements in writing</li>
		<li>Being flexible on timing and minor details</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>When Disagreements Arise</h3>
	<p><strong>Step 1: Direct Communication</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Schedule a face-to-face conversation</li>
		<li>Listen to their concerns</li>
		<li>Look for compromise solutions</li>
		<li>Document the conversation</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Step 2: Mediation</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>San Joaquin County offers free/low-cost mediation services</li>
		<li>Neutral third party helps find mutually acceptable solutions</li>
		<li>Less expensive and confrontational than court</li>
		<li>Agreements can be made legally binding</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Step 3: Small Claims Court</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>For disputes up to $10,000 ($12,500 for businesses)</li>
		<li>No attorney required</li>
		<li>Filing fee approximately $75-100</li>
		<li>Bring all documentation: notices, estimates, photos, correspondence</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Collecting After Judgment</h3>
	<p>If you win in small claims court but your neighbor doesn't pay:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>You can place a lien on their property</li>
		<li>Wage garnishment may be possible</li>
		<li>Collection can be pursued through legal means</li>
		<li>Interest accrues on unpaid judgments</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Special Situations</h2>

	<h3>Rental Properties</h3>
	<p>If your neighbor is a renter:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>The property owner, not tenant, is responsible for fence costs</li>
		<li>Send notices to the property owner (find via county records)</li>
		<li>Don't make agreements with tenants—they can't bind the owner</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>New Construction</h3>
	<p>When one property is newly built or subdivided:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>The developer may have already installed fencing</li>
		<li>Check CC&Rs for fence maintenance responsibilities</li>
		<li>Original fence may have been entirely on one lot</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Trees and Vegetation</h3>
	<p>If trees or bushes function as a "natural fence":</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Generally not covered by fence cost-sharing laws</li>
		<li>Different rules apply to tree maintenance</li>
		<li>Consider whether natural barriers meet your needs before building</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Fence Etiquette Beyond the Law</h2>
	<p>Good neighbor relationships involve more than legal compliance:</p>

	<h3>Before Building</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Discuss plans informally before sending legal notices</li>
		<li>Consider the fence appearance from both sides</li>
		<li>Schedule construction to minimize disruption</li>
		<li>Warn neighbors before noisy work</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>The "Good Side Out" Tradition</h3>
	<p>Traditionally, the "good side" (finished side) faces outward toward neighbors. While not legally required, many consider this good etiquette. Alternatives include:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Good-neighbor style fencing:</strong> Same appearance on both sides</li>
		<li><strong>Alternating boards:</strong> Boards alternate between sides</li>
		<li><strong>Discussion:</strong> Some neighbors prefer structural side for plant support</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Ongoing Maintenance</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Maintain your fence so it doesn't become an eyesore</li>
		<li>Address repairs promptly</li>
		<li>Clean your side of the fence regularly</li>
		<li>Control vegetation that might damage the fence</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Written Agreements</h2>
	<p>Even when the law is clear, written agreements prevent misunderstandings:</p>

	<h3>What to Include</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Exact location of fence (on line or offset)</li>
		<li>Material specifications and height</li>
		<li>Total cost and each party's share</li>
		<li>Payment timeline</li>
		<li>Who hires and manages the contractor</li>
		<li>Future maintenance responsibilities</li>
		<li>What happens if fence needs replacement</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Making It Official</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Both parties sign and date</li>
		<li>Each keeps a copy</li>
		<li>Consider notarization for larger projects</li>
		<li>For major agreements, recording with the county provides notice to future owners</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Summary: Your Rights and Responsibilities</h2>

	<h3>You Have the Right To:</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Request neighbor contribution to reasonable boundary fence costs</li>
		<li>Receive 30-day notice before being asked to contribute</li>
		<li>Negotiate fence specifications</li>
		<li>Propose alternative solutions</li>
		<li>Seek mediation or court resolution for disputes</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>You Are Responsible For:</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Contributing to reasonable boundary fence costs when properly noticed</li>
		<li>Maintaining your share of existing boundary fences</li>
		<li>Following proper notice procedures before demanding contribution</li>
		<li>Complying with Stockton building codes and HOA requirements</li>
		<li>Acting in good faith in neighbor communications</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Conclusion: Building Fences and Relationships</h2>
	<p>Understanding California's Good Neighbor Fence Act empowers you to navigate fence decisions fairly and legally. While the law provides a framework for cost sharing, the best outcomes come from open communication and mutual respect between neighbors. A fence built cooperatively protects not just property lines, but the relationship between those who share them.</p>

	<p>When approaching a fence project, lead with communication, follow proper procedures, and remain flexible. Your fence will stand for years—ideally, so will your good relationship with your neighbors.</p>

